:::summary
Archimedes of Syracuse (c. 287–212 BC) was the greatest mathematician and inventor of the ancient world — a genius who discovered the principles of the lever and buoyancy, calculated an approximation of pi, developed methods of measuring curved areas and volumes, and designed ingenious war machines that kept Roman armies at bay for years. His work anticipated calculus by nearly 2,000 years.
:::

